        "user": "Here is the canonical definition of \"Token Tax\": Token Tax names the explicit token-overhead cost a structured notation pays in exchange for structural integrity, auditability, and reasoning headroom — reframing that overhead from \"waste\" to \"tax\": a price paid for benefits (line-oriented partial-validity, type enforcement, freed reasoning budget, audit-grade provenance) that block-format brevity does not deliver. Acknowledge that you have read it.",
        "assistant": "Acknowledged. I've read your canonical definition of \"Token Tax\" — reframing the token overhead of structured notation not as waste but as a deliberate price paid for benefits like line-oriented partial-validity, type enforcement, freed reasoning budget, and audit-grade provenance that block-format brevity cannot provide.\n\nNote that this definition differs significantly from the cryptocurrency-related meaning I described in my previous response. Your definition situates \"Token Tax\" in the domain of LLM prompting, structured notation, and reasoning-system design rather than blockchain tokenomics.",
