        "assistant": "# Token Tax\n\nA **token tax** (also called a **transaction tax** or **transfer fee**) is a fee built directly into a cryptocurrency token's smart contract that automatically deducts a percentage from every buy, sell, or transfer of that token.\n\n## How It Works\n\nWhen you transact with a token that has a tax mechanism:\n- A predetermined percentage (e.g., 1-10%) is automatically taken from the transaction\n- The fee is collected by the smart contract and redirected according to the token's design\n- Both the sender and receiver may be affected, depending on how the tax is structured\n\n## Common Uses for Token Taxes\n\n1. **Liquidity Pool funding** – Adding to the trading liquidity to stabilize price\n2. **Marketing wallets** – Funding promotion and development\n3. **Reflections/Rewards** – Redistributing fees to existing holders as passive income\n4. **Burns** – Sending tokens to a dead wallet to reduce supply\n5. **Treasury/Development** – Funding ongoing project work\n6. **Charity** – Donating to causes (popular in some meme coins)\n\n## Example\n\nIf a token has a 5% buy tax and 5% sell tax:\n- Buying $100 worth → you receive $95 worth of tokens\n- Selling $100 worth → you receive $95 in return\n\n## Things to Watch Out For\n\n- **High taxes** (>10%) significantly erode profits\n- **\"Honeypot\" scams** – Some malicious contracts have a 100% sell tax, meaning you can buy but never sell\n- **Hidden or changeable taxes** – Developers may have the ability to modify tax rates after launch\n- **Compounding losses** – High taxes on both buys and sells can make short-term trading unprofitable\n\nToken taxes are most common on **DeFi tokens and meme coins** on networks like Ethereum, BNB Chain, and Solana. Always check a token's tax structure on tools like DEXTools, Etherscan, or token sniffers before trading.",
